\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current abstract frames the question.
 This is my low-brow attempt to understand things.
 The writing style that will follow below will be extremely informal, loose,
 having the shape of a diary or personal notes, with a lot of editorializing
 and stream-of-consciousness thinking.
 It is not structured as an exposition or some tight article meant for a
 peer-reviewed journal.
 Lots of what will be written down will be half-formed, incorrect, misleading,
 confused.
 Such flaws may or may not be corrected at a later date.
 Frankly, I'm writing this for myself, and not for you.
 Maybe later, the notes here can be converted into something formal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the general setting; my frame of mind in posing this question.
 I'm wondering is there is a non-QFT approach to the problem.
 That is, rather than assuming QFT, Unruh radiation, Hawking radiation,
 etc.
 I'm wondering if there is a classical or semi-classical footing that can
 be given.
 Perhaps this sounds crazy or absurd, since the original Bekenstein and
 Hawking arguments take QFT as foundational.
 But now that it has been given, can we backtrack and find some simpler
 construction that connects conventional dynamical systems and conventional
 geometry, without having to invoke QFT? Perhaps this is foolish, but I'm
 a fool, so there we go.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I'm thinking 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

this has something to do with spin connections
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because there is very little else that it could be, if the entropy has
 a classical, non-quantum source.
 That is, my efforts here will be almost entirely based on classical mechanics
 and conventional dynamical systems theory, rather than invoking quantum
 from the get-go.
 The hope is to either find a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 description, and, if not, then expose why there is no such description.
 Now, again, perhaps this sounds foolish, as there is an implicit 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset

 floating around.
 I'm hoping that the presence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 does not necessarily imply quantization; so, for example, Fourier transforms
 do not require 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 even though they are conventionally used to construct QM.
 In a similar way, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 is not required to define Poincare duality or any other common concepts
 from differential geometry, even though cohomological results are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naturally quantized
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 So, more precisely, I'm trying to avoid invoking second quantization and
 Feynmann path integrals.
 I'm entirely happy to call a Dirac field and Pauli exclusion as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

purely classical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 objects.
 Mostly because these follow from Riemannian geometry and from Clifford
 algebras.
\end_layout

